stress -- tEpilogue -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aConstant J. Mews's groundbreaking work reveals the wide world of medieval letters. Looking beyond the cathedral and the cloister for his investigations, and taking a broad view of intellectual practice in the Middle Ages, Mews demands that we expand our horizons as we explore the history of ideas. Alongside his cutting-edge work on Abelard, he has been a leader in the study of medieval women writers, paying heed to Hildegard and Heloise in particular. Mews has also expanded our knowledge of medieval music, and its theoretical foundations. In Mews' Middle Ages, the world of ideas always belongs to a larger world: one that is cultural, gendered and politicized. The essays in this volume pay tribute to Constant, in spirit and in content, revealing a nuanced and integrated vision of the intellectual history of the medieval West.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aCivilization, Medieval. 0aIntellectual lifexHistory. 4aCultural Studies. 4aHigh Middle Ages. 4aHistory, Art History, and Archaeology. 4aPhilosophy. 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh  aIntellectual, philosophy, theology, gender.1 aAdams, Tracy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBollermann, Karen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aColish, Marcia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCrossley, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGreen, Karen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHoward, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJames, Carolyn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLahav, Rina,